## 3. Booking State Machine Design and Transition Rules

The booking state transitions will follow a strict state validation check schema. Any attempt to skip or violate the lifecycle sequence will respond with `400 Bad Request` payload error.

### State Transition Diagram
```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2
    [*] --> pending : Customer creates booking
    pending --> accepted : Sarthi accepts booking
    pending --> cancelled : 60s timeout / Customer cancels early
    accepted --> in_progress : Sarthi starts booking (Manual, no GPS validation)
    accepted --> cancelled : Customer cancels late (Rs.50 fee tracked in metadata)
    in_progress --> completed : Sarthi completes work
    completed --> paid : Payment verified successfully (via verification hook)
    cancelled --> [*]
    paid --> [*]
```

### Transition Rule Constraints Matrix

| Current State | Target State | Triggered By | Constraint Rules |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `pending` | `accepted` | Worker | Sarthi must not be blocked (`isBlocked !== true`) |
| `pending` | `cancelled` | Customer / System | Allowed freely. Automatically triggered if 60s timeout occurs |
| `accepted` | `in_progress` | Worker | Sarthi manually activates work start (No GPS validation check enforced) |
| `accepted` | `cancelled` | Customer | Allowed. Late cancellation tracks a flat Rs.50 fee in booking `metadata.cancellationFee` (no actual wallet deduction) |
| `in_progress` | `completed` | Worker | Sarthi submits complete. Transitions to completed. |
| `completed` | `paid` | System (Payment) | Triggered upon successful signature verification check in `verifyPaymentSignature`. |

